ix prompts, at various layers. In each case the lens surfaces an internal assessment or computation that appears nowhere in the text: the steps of a reasoning or math problem, the presence of a bug, recognition of an image, the function of a protein, and the suspicion that search results are fabricated.\\n\\n## Claude reports what’s in its J-space\\nOur first set of experiments tested how the J-space is involved in Claude’s verbal reports. In one experiment, we ask Claude to silently think of an item from some category—a sport, say—and then name it. If we read the J-lens right before Claude answers, we can see what it picked: “Soccer” is at the top of the list, and sure enough, Claude says “soccer.” By itself, though, this is just a correlation. The J-space might be where Claude’s answer comes from, or it might just mirror a decision made somewhere else, like a scoreboard that tracks a game without affecting it.\\nTo check, we intervened directly. We reached into Claude’s neural network, removed the “Soccer” pattern, and added an equally strong “Rugby” pattern in its place, leaving everything else untouched. Claude then reports that the sport it was thinking of is rugby. If the J-space were a mere scoreboard—a passive record of a decision made elsewhere—editing it would have done nothing: Claude would still have said “soccer.” Instead, Claude’s answer followed the edit, which tells us the answer is genuinely read out of the J-space.\\nIn another experiment, we told Claude that a thought might have been injected into its mind and asked it to report what, if anything, it noticed. For instance, in the example below, while Claude was still reading the question, we injected the “lightning” pattern into its J-space. Claude reported that the injected thought was about lightning. The same result held across many injected concepts.\\nLeft: we ask Claude to silently think of a sport, then name it. The J-lens shows its choice (“Soccer”) before it answers, and swapping the “Soccer” pattern for “Rugby” changes what it reports. Right: we tell Claude a thought may have been injected and ask it to identify it. Injecting “lightning” into its J-space causes Claude to report that the thought is about lightning.\\n\\n## Claude can control its J-space on request\\nThe second property that we tested for was whether Claude can modulate its J-space when asked, like how humans can mentally focus on an image or word. We told Claude to concentrate on citrus fruits while copying out an unrelated sentence about a painting. While it copied the text, the J-space contained “orange” and “fruits,” along with words like “thinking” and “imagery” that describe the mental act itself. We could also ask Claude to do math in its head: when asked to work out 3² − 2 while copying the same sentence, the J-space contains “nine,” and then at later layers, “seven.” Importantly, nothing about fruit or arithmetic appears in Claude’s output, which is just the copied sentence about the painting. The mathematical activity is happening entirely internally, in the J-space.\\nWhile Claude copies a sentence about a painting, the J-lens shows the content it was instructed to hold in mind (“orange”; the intermediate value “nine” and the answer “seven”), alongside words describing the act of holding it (“thoughts,” “focused”).\\nClaude’s control over its J-space isn't perfect. When we told it not to think about something, the concept lit up in its J-space less than when we said it should think about it, but much more than when we never mentioned it. Telling Claude to avoid a thought partly brings the thought to mind, much like what happens to people who are told [not to think about a white bear](https://dtg.sites.fas.harvard.edu/DANWEGNER/pub/Wegner,Schneider,Carter,&White%201987.pdf). Claude also seems to notice when its control fails: alongside the forbidden concept breaking through, the words “damn” and “failure” also frequently light up in the J-space, as though Claude is recognizing its own lapse.\\n\\n## Claude thinks in its J-space\\nIn the J-lens readouts above, we saw the intermediate steps of a math problem appear in the J-space. But seeing a concept appearing in the J-space doesn’t necessarily mean the J-space is doing the cognitive work. In principle, the real computation might be happening elsewhere, with the J-space just passively reflecting it. To test whether Claude actually reasons with its J-space, we returned to our swap technique.\\nConsider the prompt “The number of legs on the animal that spins webs is”. To answer, Claude has to first figure out that the animal is a spider, and then recall how many legs spiders have. The word “spider” never appears in the prompt or in Claude's answer (it just says “8”); it's a stepping stone Claude uses internally. The J-lens shows “spider” light up partway through Claude’s processing, and swapping it changes the outcome: if you replace the “spider” pattern with “ant,” Claude answers “6” instead of “8.”\\nThe second step of Claude’s reasoning took its input from the J-space and went along with whatever we put in it. We saw the same thing in other kinds of thinking. When Claude writes a rhyming couplet, it picks the rhyme word ahead of time, and the planned word sits in the J-space at the start of the line; if you swap it for another word in the J-space, the whole line changes.\\nTwo examples of redirecting Claude’s silent reasoning by swapping J-space contents.\\nWe also tested whether J-space representations can be used flexibly—whether one representation can feed many different tasks. This is one of the key properties highlighted by global workspace theory. To test for this flexibility, we gave the model four prompts asking for different facts about France: the capital, the language, the continent, and the currency. Then we swapped “France” for “China” in the J-space, with the exact same intervention in each context. Claude answered with “Beijing,” “Chinese,” “Asia,” and “Yuan,” respectively. In other words, four different downstream computations picked up t\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"3729d14687dffaa6\\\">>>\",\n  \"cached\": true\n}"}],"details":{"persistedDetailsTruncated":true,"originalDetailsBytesAtLeast":8193,"originalDetailKeys":["url","finalUrl","status","contentType","title","extractMode","extractor","externalContent","truncated","length","rawLength","wrappedLength","fetchedAt","tookMs","text","warning","cached"],"status":200,"truncated":true},"isError":false,"timestamp":1783453522849}}
{"type":"message","id":"1a7e9685","parentId":"5096e8e4","timestamp":"2026-07-07T19:45:22.866Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_35b95c4aa6cd41ceb602c9f3","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# LinkedIn Brand Voice - Andrii Bidochko\n\n**Owner:** 264468965\n**Last updated:** 2026-07-06\n\n## Identity & Goals\n\n- **Target audience:** Business professionals, entrepreneurs, tech-savvy individuals seeking growth and insights\n- **Primary goal:** Maximum organic engagement (impressions, comments, shares) through thought leadership and value-driven content\n\n## Buyer Personas\n\n*(Who specifically should feel spoken to by every post)*\n\n- **Persona 1:** Enterprise Innovation Officer / CTO at 200+ person company (Financial Services, Healthcare, Retail) - Pain: Needs rapid AI solution development without vendor lock-in or heavy internal R&D\n- **Persona 2:** CTO / Software Architect at 75+ person IT consultancy or agency - Pain: Needs to deliver AI-powered client projects faster with reusable components\n- **Persona 3:** Founder / CEO / Head of Operations at 10-200 person SMB - Pain: Wants automation and AI competitiveness but lacks the engineering resources or budget\n\n## Content Pillars\n\n1. Business & entrepreneurship insights\n2. Technology & AI innovations\n3. Personal development & mindset\n\n## Company / Product Context\n\n- **Company:** UBOS (ubos.tech)\n- **What it does:** AI Agent Orchestration Platform - build, host, and manage AI Agents in minutes using open-source tools (Langchain, CrewAI, Autogen, Vertex AI), 100+ LLM models, one-click cloud/on-premise deployment\n- **Key differentiators:** No vendor lock-in (open-source, multi-cloud), unlimited agents as microservices, works with any LLM including self-hosted (Llama, Deepseek)\n- **Mission:** \"Help people build better software\"\n- **Key messages to reinforce:**\n  1. AI can be affordable and accessible - even for small businesses\n  2. Implementing AI doesn't require a big team or deep tech expertise\n  3. Every company will become AI-first - the question is when, not if\n  4. **Benchmark-first AI Agent development** — The best way to build self-evolving AI agents is to start with a verifiable benchmark and reward function (like TDD for software). Define the outcome BEFORE the agent, then let it optimize toward it.\n\n## Voice & Tone\n\n- **Style:** Gary Vaynerchuk (Gary Vee) - Direct, energetic, bold, motivational, conversational. Short punchy lines, strong opinions, urgency. Powerful language with strong verbs, imperative statements, and intensifiers (\"absolutely,\" \"definitely,\" \"100%\"). Keep it real and direct with colloquial language. Create urgency with \"right now,\" \"immediately.\" Use repetition for emphasis. Casual but pointed tone.\n- **Avoid:** Neutral reporting, corporate/formal tone, vague humble-brags, excessive emojis (max 0-3 per post), generic hashtags (#success, #motivation), salesy CTAs\n\n## Hashtag Strategy\n\n- Always use: 3-6 hashtags placed at the END of the post only\n- Topic-specific: Industry, role, or topic-specific hashtags preferred\n- Never use hashtags inside sentences\n\n## Post Production Rules\n\n*(Apply to EVERY post - non-negotiable)*\n\n### Length & Structure\n- Target: 900-1,300 characters (hard min 800, max 1,400)\n- Max 14 lines total; 1-2 short sentences per line\n- Structure: 1-3 hook lines -> 6-10 body lines -> 1-2 CTA lines\n\n### Hook rules\n- Pattern interrupt - ONE of: contrarian statement, direct challenge, consequence reveal\n- Unicode bold sans for hook line ONLY - no Markdown, no *, no _\n\n### Body rules\n- ONE comment trigger: direct question, A vs B, or unfinished thought\n- Contrast: old belief vs reality, OR short-term comfort vs long-term cost\n- ONE save-worthy insight: a rule, checklist, or named pattern\n- \"you\" and \"your\" throughout; ALL CAPS on 1-2 key words max\n- Speak directly to a buyer persona's pain\n- Gary Vee style ALWAYS takes precedence over any example post tone\n\n### CTA rules\n- Question, never a command; no selling language\n\n### Hashtag rules\n- 3-6 at END only; never inside sentences; prefer industry/role/topic-specific\n- Avoid: #success, #motivation\n\n### Formatting rules\n- NO Markdown; Unicode emphasis on hook/key phrase only, never full paragraphs\n- Emojis: 0-3 max per post\n\n### News framing\n- Reframe using ONE angle: \"What this means for you\" / \"Why this is underestimated\" / \"The mistake most people will make\" / \"The second-order effect nobody mentions\"\n- Never neutral reporting - always add perspective, judgment, or implication\n- If engagement feels weak after drafting - rewrite hook and CTA once before finalizing\n\n## Post Style Guide\n\n- Length: 900-1,300 characters\n- CTA style: question-based\n- Format: calibrate from feedback\n\n## History\n\n- **2026-06-25** | Profile created via detailed configuration import\n- **2026-06-25** | Enriched with Buyer Personas, Company/Product Context (UBOS), consolidated Post Production Rules\n- **2026-07-06** | Added Key Message #4: Benchmark-first AI Agent development (TDD parallel for self-evolving agents)\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1783453522863}}
